{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"65cae1ce-44d1-4517-92f9-da6b7ac83f17","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()` (MSTest) instead — it's more precise, lets you assert on the specific line that throws, and allows further inspection of the exception:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName); // optional: verify details\n}\n```\n\n**Why**: `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line in the test throws, masking bugs. `Assert.ThrowsException` scopes the assertion to the exact call.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2251d829-03a8-486d-96f5-95d275db7b7f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to modernize a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general coding question - I don't need to search the filesystem or use tools for this.\n\nThe modern approach is to use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>()` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>()` (xUnit/NUnit) instead of the `[ExpectedException]` attribute.","outputTokens":291,"requestId":"BC29:18B6D6:1E1025C:2150C6C:69FA9625"},"id":"4fe7de6a-e388-4d03-86f8-09f8b3430d8c","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:15:23.606Z","parentId":"703d0653-295e-491b-a009-50dc9d89ceaa"}
